{
  "doc_id": "17757",
  "text": "Two other bacterial species, C amycolatum and S aureus, were also isolated from the wounds of the cat in Figure 6 Inguinal area 3 months after hospitalization (January 2016) this case report. Both are components of the normal flora of normal human and animal skin and mucous membranes. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] However, they can also be pathogenic in some circumstances. In particular, C amycolatum is increasingly being recognized as an important pathogen of humans with multidrug resistance to commonly used antibiotics, although it is typically susceptible to vancomycin. [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] Over the course of the disease process, C amycolatum was isolated from the cat in this report four times, despite antimicrobial therapy, and likely contributed to the severity of the wounds in this cat. Given that S aureus can normally colonize cat skin, [CITATION_5] the significance of the S aureus isolate was less clear, but it may also have played a role in secondary infection.",
